# WGPL — architecture rules

WGPL (WireGuard Peer Lite) is a disconnected Python CLI that manages WireGuard
*peers*. ALWAYS respect these invariants.

## Layers (one direction only)

`cli.py` (Typer / presentation) → `core.py` (business) → `db.py` / `wireguard.py` (infra).

- `cli.py` MUST NOT import `db.py`; use `core.ensure_database()`, `core.list_interfaces()`, `core.list_peers()`, etc.
- `core.py` MUST NOT import Typer or format output (no stdout/stderr writes; use iterators such as `dump_database_lines()`).
- `db.py` / `wireguard.py` MUST NOT contain business logic.

## Peer lifecycle and IP allocation

- `_is_peer_active()` is the SSOT for whether a peer occupies resources (not soft-deleted and not expired).
- IP pool reservation (`_pool_used_ips`, `allocate_peer_ip`) MUST use `_is_peer_active()`, not `deleted_at IS NULL` alone.
- Expired peers release their IP for new allocations; `peer prune` removes expired/soft-deleted rows physically.
- When reusing an IP held by an expired peer, `add_peer` / `peer update` soft-delete the inactive row so partial unique indexes allow the INSERT/UPDATE.
- `get_peer_status()` and `get_effective_dns()` live in `core.py`; the CLI must not duplicate lifecycle or DNS cascade logic.

## Scope

- IPv4-only address pools and peer IPs. Document this limitation; do not add IPv6 support without an explicit design change.

## SSOT and synchronization

- The SQLite database is the single source of truth (SSOT).
- NEVER sync WireGuard automatically in `add_peer` / `remove_peer`.
  State reaches the OS only via `wgpl apply` (local) or
  `wgpl interface export | ssh ... wg syncconf` (remote).

## Concurrency and integrity

- Multi-step writes go inside `db.transaction()` (`BEGIN EXCLUSIVE`).
- Compute the free IP (`allocate_peer_ip`) and INSERT the peer in the
  SAME transaction to avoid IP collisions.

## Security

- Enforce `chmod 600` on the DB file on every connection.
- Generate keys with `cryptography` (x25519) in memory; do not rely on `wg` to create them.
- `subprocess` with argument lists, NEVER `shell=True`.
- SQL always parameterized (`?`).
- Domain errors inherit from `WgplException` (`exceptions.py`); `cli.py` catches them
  and exits with `sys.exit(1)`.

## Output contract

- This is a Typer CLI, NOT a web framework. Ignore FastAPI/Django suggestions.
- With `--json`: data on stdout, logs and errors on stderr.

## Validation (same as CI)

- `uv run ruff check src/ tests/`
- `uv run mypy src/`
- `uv run pytest`

## Documentation language

- All project documentation, AI context files (rules, skills, memory), and code
  comments/docstrings MUST be written in **English**.
- User-facing CLI help text and error messages in `cli.py` remain in English
  (already the case).
- Conversations with the user may be in any language; generated artifacts are not.
